**Rate Limiting**:
*   Drogon has built-in support for rate limiting using `Filters`. A simple approach would be to create a `RateLimitingFilter` similar to `AuthMiddleware`.
*   **Conceptual `RateLimitingFilter`**:
    *   It would track requests based on IP address or authenticated user ID.
    *   Use an in-memory counter or Redis to store request counts within a time window.
    *   If a user exceeds the limit, it would return a `429 Too Many Requests` response.

    ```cpp
    // Example: src/middleware/RateLimitingFilter.h
    #pragma once
    #include <drogon/HttpFilter.h>
    class RateLimitingFilter : public drogon::HttpFilter<RateLimitingFilter> {
    public:
        RateLimitingFilter() = default;
        void doFilter(const drogon::HttpRequestPtr &req,
                      drogon::FilterCallback &&fcb,
                      drogon::FilterChainCallback &&fccb) override;
    };

    // Example: src/middleware/RateLimitingFilter.cc
    #include "RateLimitingFilter.h"
    #include <drogon/drogon.h>
    #include <spdlog/spdlog.h>
    #include <unordered_map>
    #include <chrono>

    // Simple in-memory rate limiter (not suitable for distributed systems)
    // For production, use Redis.
    static std::unordered_map<std::string, std::chrono::steady_clock::time_point> lastRequestTime;
    static std::mutex rateLimitMutex;
    const std::chrono::seconds THROTTLE_WINDOW = std::chrono::seconds(1);
    const int MAX_REQUESTS_PER_WINDOW = 5; // Example: 5 requests per second

    void RateLimitingFilter::doFilter(const drogon::HttpRequestPtr &req,
                                       drogon::FilterCallback &&fcb,
                                       drogon::FilterChainCallback &&fccb) {
        std::string clientIdentifier = req->getPeerAddr().toIpPort(); // Use IP address

        std::lock_guard<std::mutex> lock(rateLimitMutex);
        auto now = std::chrono::steady_clock::now();

        // This is a very basic implementation. A real one would use a token bucket or sliding window.
        // This just checks time since last request.
        if (lastRequestTime.count(clientIdentifier) &&
            (now - lastRequestTime[clientIdentifier] < THROTTLE_WINDOW)) {
            // Need a more sophisticated counter
            // For now, let's just illustrate the concept.
            spdlog::warn("Rate limit exceeded for client: {}", clientIdentifier);
            auto resp = drogon::HttpResponse::newHttpResponse();
            resp->setStatusCode(drogon::k429TooManyRequests);
            resp->setBody("{\"code\":429,\"message\":\"Too Many Requests\"}");
            resp->setContentTypeCode(drogon::CT_APPLICATION_JSON);
            fcb(resp);
            return;
        }

        lastRequestTime[clientIdentifier] = now; // Update last request time

        fccb(); // Continue
    }
    ```
